</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Laidlaw, the Ontario-based waste services and transportation group, expects
to become North America's biggest hazardous waste operator with a proposed
deal to acquire a subsidiary of Union Pacific, the US railroad conglomerate.
Laidlaw has signed an exclusive agreement with Union Pacific to negotiate
the purchase of United States Pollution Control, which operates several
landfills, service centres and other hazardous waste facilities in the
western US.
The purchase price is expected to be about USDollars 225m, plus unspecified
financial and environmental obligations. Laidlaw's board is due to approve
the deal in mid-November, and regulatory approvals should be completed by
early next year.
Laidlaw said the addition of US Pollution would lift its hazardous-waste
revenues to more than Dollars 800m a year.
The hazardous waste business has been marked by fierce competition and
tightening environmental rules. However, Mr Jim Bullock, chief executive,
said 'these assets will make us an even stronger competitor in a rapidly
consolidating market place'.
Mr Bullock said US Pollution would expand Laidlaw's geographic coverage and
provide facilities for incineration of solid hazardous waste.
