<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In my days as a reporter three favourite rainy-day stories were: Increase In
Dog Attacks On Children, Puma On The Loose, and Dramatic Rise In Rat
Population. All three were guaranteed to cause a stir ..no matter how often
you ran them. BBC1's early evening series Here And Now starts a new batch
with 'Dramatic Rise In Rat Population'. Which of the standard variations
will they go for: 'Now they're immune to all known poisons' or 'This new
strain knows no fear' ? (7.00). C4's current affairs series, Dispatches,
brings out the discrepancies between cost and penalty for running a lorry
legally and running it illegally. Tax and insurance can cost as much as
Pounds 3,000, and proper maintenance much more, yet fines for breaking the
rules can be just a few hundred pounds, even when a fatality results (9.00).
Ludovic Kennedy presents an 80-minute report on Murder In Belgravia - The
Lucan Affair which, remarkably, promises to 'shed new light on the accepted
theory of what happened on that fateful November night'. Hard to imagine
anything new unless you claim that Lucan did not do it (10.20 BBC1).
</TEXT>
