<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Formal bids take shape for Channel 5
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Virgin, the airline and leisure group, and a number of other media consortia
are starting to prepare formal bids for the licence to run Channel 5, the
planned commercial television channel.
The Independent Television Commission, the body that regulates commercial
television, yesterday advertised the 10-year licence for Channel 5. It is
scheduled to come on stream by early 1997 and will reach between 52 per cent
and 70 per cent of the UK.
Mr Robert Devereux, chairman of Virgin Communications, confirmed that his
company was likely to mount a bid, although he said it had not yet taken a
final decision.
He said Virgin envisaged launching a 'general entertainment channel' which
would be 'slightly younger and slightly more up-market' than existing
terrestrial television services.
Virgin could face fierce competition from other bidders. Mr Ward Thomas,
chairman of Yorkshire-Tyne Tees Television, confirmed that his company is to
bid.
Mr Thomas said he had already identified a number of prospective investors
interested in forming a consortium, including several US concerns. 'Our
problem isn't attracting enough investment, it's deciding which investors to
choose,' he added.
Channel 5 Broadcasting, a consortium including Time Warner of the US,
Pearson - the media group that owns the Financial Times - and the MAI
services group, is also about to make a final decision as to whether to
proceed with an application.
NBC, the US television network, and CanWest Global Communications of Canada
have similarly expressed interest in the channel.
Some prospective bidders yesterday voiced concern about the uncertainty as
to what proportion of the UK would be covered by Channel 5.
Some of its original frequencies have been reallocated by the government for
digital terrestrial television. The ITC is applying for international
permission for extra frequencies for Channel 5, and is confident that it
will reach 70 per cent of UK homes or close to that figure.
The consensus among prospective bidders is that Channel 5 will be
commercially feasible as long as it reaches more than 60 per cent of the UK.
Editorial Comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
