<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Weighty tome sends investment banks reeling: Effects of the
EU's capital adequacy directive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain has long prided itself on the rigour with which it polices its
securities and banking markets. Its tough stance, regulators argue, has
increased confidence in the London markets to the point where roughly 25 per
cent of the world's equity trades are executed there.
Yet Britain's investment banks are arguing that the tough regulatory stance
threatens to place them at a competitive disadvantage to their European
Union counterparts.
The bone of contention is the EU Capital Adequacy Directive, a lengthy tome
whose goal is to ensure that member states go to equal lengths in policing
the capital requirements of their own investment banks.
The bankers say they fear that French and German regulators will not enforce
the rules, which take effect in 1996, with equal vigour, giving banks based
in those countries a competitive edge.
'We figure that this directive means that for our trading position in UK
equities, we will need two to three times more capital than we now do,' said
the director of operations at one large UK investment bank. 'And banks
allocate capital on the basis of return. If a particular business isn't
earning the same return, we have to ask ourselves whether we should still be
in it.'
Moreover, the bankers say, it will force them to revamp their information
systems to allow them to report to regulators in the manner stipulated by
the directive. 'We are looking at all our businesses around the world to see
where business is booked and how it is booked and to see if we ought to do
things differently,' said a lawyer for one US-based investment bank. When
the study is completed, he said, the bank may well decide to book business
outside of London.
The difficulty, UK investment bankers say, is that the business varies so
widely among EU countries that it is impossible to design a single regime
which would be suitable for all. For one thing, while most of the securities
industry on the Continent is conducted through a division of a universal
bank, in the UK many of the largest players are securities firms with a
banking arm attached.
The directive takes views on this split in the business that UK firms say
will work to their disadvantage in several ways. First, the directive makes
a distinction between the capital needed to back a 'banking book' and that
needed to back a 'trading book'.
When it comes to the trading book, the directive takes a different view from
that of UK securities regulators. First, it says that capital must be held
against both the counterparty risk (the risk of the financial failure of one
party) and the market risk of each security.
In the UK, the Securities and Futures Authority which regulates the industry
has allowed firms to take account of both factors in a single calculation.
Moreover, unlike in the UK, the directive does not take account of hedged
positions - holdings in securities whose risks offset each other - the way
current regulations do.
Complicating matters, the Treasury has proposed interpreting the directive
definition of 'liquid' securities very narrowly so that only holdings of the
largest UK equities will fall into that category. Less liquid stocks require
higher capital backing.
Also, the directive's 'large exposures' rule creates a hard limit on the
value of transactions an investment bank can have with a single
counterparty. In the UK, investment banks may increase their exposure so
long as they also increase the capital they hold against that position.
'The CAD is going to require us to have real-time calculation of our large
exposures,' said a lawyer for one US-based investment bank. 'You will have
to know what your exposure is to a single credit all the time and around the
world.'
</TEXT>
