<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Heathrow tunnel collapse findings due next week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Preliminary findings of an inquiry into the collapse of a tunnel under
construction at Heathrow airport are expected to be announced early next
week, the airport operator BAA said yesterday.
The outcome could have significant financial implications for other large
transport projects using the new Austrian tunnelling method involved in the
collapse at one of two underground stations being built at Heathrow.
Work has halted on both stations which will form part of a Pounds 300m rail
link between the airport and Paddington station in central London. The
existing Terminal Four station on the London Underground remained closed
yesterday for safety checks. BAA hopes to reopen it in 10 days.
Construction has also stopped at two other London Underground stations, at
London Bridge and Waterloo in south London, part of the Pounds 1.9bn Jubilee
underground line extension. All four stations were using the new Austrian
tunnelling method.
London Bridge station alone is expected to cost Pounds 76m. This price could
rise sharply if it was decided that a more expensive tunnelling technique
was required.
Waterloo station is part of a Pounds 157m contract which includes
constructing a rail tunnel between Green Park and Waterloo and building a
new station at Westminster. Only Waterloo station is using the new Austrian
method.
This technique allows tunnels to be excavated by conventional diggers,
rather than by expensive tunnel-boring machines. The walls of the tunnel are
then covered with a steel mesh before being sprayed with fast-drying
concrete.
Two inquiries have been launched into the tunnel collapse. The first of
these led by Mr David Williams, BAA technical director, is due to announce
its preliminary finding next week. A second inquiry by the Health and Safety
Executive will also investigate 'the broader implications for the use of the
new Austrian tunnelling method'.
It is expected to examine whether the technique, developed for rocky ground,
is suitable for soft London clay where it is being used for the first time
on a large scale on the Heathrow and Jubilee stations.
Questions were raised previously about the suitability of the new method for
different ground conditions following the collapse of a tunnel in Munich in
September resulting in the death of three people.
Engineers investigating the Heathrow collapse will have to consider whether
ground conditions were at fault or if design flaws or faulty workmanship
caused the failure.
BAA and London Underground stressed yesterday that work had halted on only a
small part of the Heathrow Express and Jubilee Line projects.
More than 3,000 cu m of concrete have been poured into the collapsed tunnel
sections to stabilise the ground.
Still to be determined is the extent of any construction delay and the
effect on the cost of two of Britain's biggest transport projects.
</TEXT>
