<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Superstores forced from fresh pastures: Planning consent
will become increasingly hard to come by
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If the era of rapid superstore and shopping centre development in the UK was
already drawing to a close, yesterday's report from the environment select
committee may hasten its end.
Should the committee's proposals be implemented - and environment secretary
Mr John Gummer said he would consider them 'carefully and positively' - they
would make it significantly harder to get planning permission for retail
developments outside towns.
Signs of a policy change emerged last year, with publication of a new
planning policy guidance note, called PPG6, which emphasised the need to
protect the 'vitality and viability' of town centres. Its main effect was
thought likely to be to prevent planning consent being given for new large
out-of-town shopping centres, such as Merry Hill in the West Midlands, or
the MetroCentre in Tyne and Wear.
In fact PPG6 has already been used by local and central government to clamp
down on both shopping centre and superstore developments - especially since
Mr Gummer has involved himself personally in the planning process.
A report last week by Mr Paul Smiddy, food retailing analyst at the Japanese
investment bank Nomura, found the percentage of successful planning appeals
had fallen from 60 per cent before PPG6 to about 30 per cent in the past
three months.
Of 15 planning appeals considered by Department of the Environment
inspectors this year, eight were allowed, but of 18 which went to Mr Gummer,
only one was approved.
This has forced supermarket groups such as J. Sainsbury, Tesco and Argyll,
owner of Safeway, which have built several hundred out-of-town superstores
over the past decade, to cut their expansion plans. Tesco and Sainsbury have
launched revamped town-centre formats, called Metro and Central
respectively.
Sainsbury now expects to add 25 per cent less floorspace in 1995-96 and
beyond than it was forecasting a year ago.
The three groups yesterday defended the need for large, out-of-town sites.
Safeway said the report 'failed to recognise what weekly bulk-food shoppers
require'.
It added: 'Supermarket customers will not return to daily high-street
shopping, even with fully integrated planning and transport policies.'
Tesco said superstores provided 'essential' facilities for shoppers with
young children, and for the disabled. It said families typically bought
80lbs of shopping in one trip.
Some groups warned that banning out-of-town developments would not in itself
revitalise town centres, unless they provided better facilities - including
sufficient car parking - for shoppers. The British Property Federation
warned that retail development 'responds to social change, it does not
create it'.
'Restrictions on certain kinds of retail development will not necessarily
secure the vitality of existing town centres,' the federation added.
Mr Richard Wright, vice-president of the British Council of Shopping
Centres, said that while it was correct to support town centres, each had
different problems. He added: 'It might be appropriate in a historic town to
consider edge-of-town developments to relieve congestion and protect a
unique environment.'
The Consumers' Association warned that the report risked condemning
customers to a future of high prices - to pay for town centre redevelop-ment
 -and of limited choice.
The Council for the Protection of Rural England said planning policies
needed to be revised 'to stop sprawl and help breathe new life into our town
centres and high streets'.
</TEXT>
