<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Pollution cost plea to industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK's pollution inspectorate has asked for volunteers from industry to
try to prove that tighter environmental controls are not as expensive as
critics think.
Dr David Slater, director and chief inspector of the Inspectorate of
Pollution, last night called for 'a handful' of companies to come forward
and co-operate.
The companies and the inspectorate would look at the effect of controls on
chemical emissions and efficiency, and the economics of integrated pollution
control (IPC) - the regime the regulators have been enforcing for the past
three years under the Environmental Protection Act.
Dr Slater was giving the annual lecture of the north-west region of the
Chemical Industries Association at the University of Manchester Institute of
Science and Technology.
He said the inspectorate believed in IPC, but not blindly. It needed to see
what the policy was actually doing by collaborating with companies affected
by it. 'I am sure we would find that IPC is not, overall, as expensive as
some might have us believe.'
On keeping costs reasonable, Dr Slater welcomed the appointment by the
government of an independent advisory committee to provide the inspectorate
with expert external opinion. But he stressed that companies still had to
spend money to monitor what they were doing to the environment.
He said: 'We recognise that monitoring can be almost a bottomless pit as far
as money is concerned.' But he added: 'If you can't measure it, then you
can't manage it.'
</TEXT>
