<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Delays likely on building society law changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministerial decisions about changing the rules governing the way building
societies operate are set to be delayed beyond the original deadline for the
far-reaching government review - which could mean the changes would not
become law before the next general election in 1996 or 1997.
The two-stage review of societies' powers and duties of accountability to
the millions of customers who own them was launched in January. At that
time, the Treasury said it intended to complete the work by the end of this
year. This summer Mr Anthony Nelson, the Treasury minister, insisted that
this timetable would be met.
But some of the largest societies have already told the Treasury that they
will be unable to meet next Wednesday's deadline for comments on the second
stage of the review.
There is thus little time for ministers to take advice and reach decisions
before they are taken up with the work surrounding the Budget and the annual
public spending statement at the end of this month.
The Treasury said yesterday that it was still aiming to complete the review
by the end of the year.
Timing of the review has already suffered one setback: announcement of the
first-stage results, which had been planned for May, did not take place
until July.
One element in the delay was the extensive interest in the plans, which aim
to give societies greater freedom to raise funds, lend to small businesses
and own general insurance subsidiaries, from elsewhere in Whitehall
including Downing Street, the Department of the Environment and the
Department of Trade and Industry.
The consultation paper for the second stage of the review, published in
September, raises even broader issues about the structure of regulation for
societies and how far new measures might make them more accountable to their
members.
If, as could well be the case, the conclusions of the government's review
are not intensely party political, then legislation to bring them about
could be included in the last pre-election legislative session - probably
the one that starts in November next year. But the chances of a bill could
be lessened unless the policy can be agreed in plenty of time.
Even if the results of the government review are delayed into early next
year, they may still not fit in with the timing of the inquiry into
financial regulation by the Commons Treasury committee. The committee is to
begin hearing evidence on building societies later this month.
</TEXT>
