<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / IoD warns of fall in confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Institute of Directors said yesterday it saw no evidence of overheating
in the economy to justify a further increase in interest rates.
In its bi-monthly business opinion survey of company directors, the IoD
found that confidence in the economy and bullishness about future prospects
had fallen in October compared with August.
Directors also expressed concern about lack of demand and were worried about
meeting customer demands and cashflow.
The survey of 300 of the institute's 33,000 members revealed that in spite
of a dampened feel-good factor, 78 per cent said their company was
performing very well or fairly well overall, slightly up from the 76 per
cent who expressed that opinion in August.
Company performance remained healthy as orders and volumes were buoyant in
October. Those reporting an increase in business volume over the last six
months steadied at 63 per cent and reports of increased orders rose from 49
per cent in August to 53 per cent in October.
However, those reporting an increased profits trend slipped from 54 per cent
in August to 51 per cent last month. Investment and employment prospects
were still strong, if slightly down from the previous survey.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, Iod director general, said: 'We are still enjoying
steady, positive growth but there is now evidence that the rate of growth
was slowing even before September's (interest rate) increase.
'Bearing in mind that other indicators such as growth in earnings and broad
money supply remain low and the housing market is flat, there is no evidence
to support another interest rate rise at this stage.'
</TEXT>
