<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Lottery adverts anger charities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Charity fundraisers yesterday lodged a complaint with the Advertising
Standards Authority, the advertising watchdog, about advertisements
promoting the National Lottery in last Sunday's newspapers.
The advertisements say: 'Every time you play the National Lottery, someone
else gets a better chance.' They add: 'For every pound that you spend
playing the National Lottery, at least a quarter will go to hundreds of
worthy causes throughout the UK.'
The Institute of Charity Fundraising Managers, the fundraisers' professional
body, said it was concerned the advertisements might encourage people to
stop donating to charities and switch to buying lottery tickets, which go on
sale later this month.
Mr Stephen Lee, institute director, said charity fundraisers had long
supported the lottery but this support had always been based on the
principle that income from the National Lottery would be truly additional to
existing levels of support to our sector.
Research commissioned by the National Council for Voluntary Organisations
had estimated that the lottery could result in an annual loss of charitable
income of between Pounds 190m and Pounds 270m.
Mr Lee added: 'We were led to believe that the lottery will be promoted
primarily as a fun activity, not as a means of supporting charities and
voluntary organisations.'
</TEXT>
