<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Finance sought for driverless bus network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's first guided bus system, using computer-controlled, driverless
buses, could be in operation in Guildford, Surrey, by 2002 if private-sector
finance can be raised.
The four-mile guided bus network would be powered by electricity generated
by a purpose-built power station burning domestic waste. Guildford Rapid
Transit's buses would link the town centre with the university, a sports
centre and industrial and commercial areas.
Guided buses are cheaper to install and operate than light rail or
'supertram' systems but most British cities seeking to improve their public
transport networks, including Sheffield and Manchester, have opted for
trams. Guided bus systems are working in Germany and Australia.
The Guildford project has won the backing of the government's private
finance panel, which is attempting to encourage private-sector support for
public infrastructure projects.
The promoter, Listavia International, an engineering design consultancy, is
seeking Pounds 500,000 to carry the project forward. The bus network would
cost Pounds 103m to install with the power station costing a further Pounds
65m.
The project is at the stage where it is ready to seek planning permission.
It has been funded so far by Mr Warren Lister, managing director of
Listavia, with Pounds 60,000 of his own money.
The route would run on dedicated track, much of it elevated, with buses
picking up power from cable buried under the track where there was no
pedestrian access. At street level the buses would switch to power from
on-board batteries.
A light rail system would be 2 1/2 times as expensive to install and twice
as costly to operate. In combination with the power station, which would
sell surplus electricity to the national grid and pipe waste heat to
customers through pipes in the bus trackway, the bus network would be
profitable. The project is forecast to make a return on capital of between
12 per cent and 18 per cent a year.
Although Guildford, with a catchment-area population of 125,000, would be
the smallest UK city to have a dedicated transit system, it suffers from
city centre congestion and important areas of activity, such as the
university and commercial centres, are widely dispersed.
The bus network could carry 3,000 people an hour at peak times and is
forecast to carry 13,500 people a day. It could reduce car journeys by about
20 per cent and save about 350,000 gallons of petrol a year.
A transport survey by Surrey County Council and Guildford Borough Council
backed the idea of linking the centre of town with industrial areas and the
research park.
Construction of the network would reduce the need for city centre parking
and allow the development of some of the city's parking sites which could
become the public-sector contribution to the project.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4111 Local and Suburban Transit.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
