<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Waldegrave defends milk change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr William Waldegrave, the agriculture minister, yesterday defended
deregulation of the milk market as more supermarket groups marked up the
price of a pint by at least 2p.
Mr Waldegrave said the move to a free market inevitably meant 'winners and
losers', but the new arrangements were already 'releasing the creative
energies of the industry'. He added: 'I believe that in a comparatively
short time the change which has taken place will be seen in a more positive
light.'
The statutory Milk Marketing Board, sole buyer of milk from farmers for 61
years, was replaced yesterday by a powerful producers' co-operative, Milk
Marque, which has won control of two-thirds of supplies in England and
Wales.
Retailers yesterday blamed their higher prices on the increased cost of milk
supplied by Milk Marque to dairy manufacturers. Sainsbury, the biggest
supermarket group, joined Tesco in raising milk prices to 28p a pint, and
said butter and cheese prices would also be going up.
Safeway put its price up to 29p a pint, but will lower it to 28p today 'to
remain competitive'. Asda, the superstore chain, said its four-pint cartons
were rising by 9p, or 2.25p a pint, to 92p because the new system had
increase prices by 10 per cent.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, former agriculture minister, said in June when she
approved the new arrangements that consumers should not expect to pay more
for milk.
The agriculture ministry now says the increased prices charged to dairy
companies by Milk Marque should add no more than 0.5p to a pint. But Mr
Waldegrave denied yesterday there had been a shift in the government's view
of the benefits of deregulation.
'It's never comfortable in the short term as you move into a new era of
competition,' he said. 'But I'm a firm believer that competition is the best
way in the long term of benefiting consumer interests.'
His comments failed to placate the newly named Dairy Industry Federation,
which represents milk processors. It is preparing to submit its case
claiming abuse of monopoly power by Milk Marque to the Office of Fair
Trading.
Industry analysts expect the rise in milk prices to be short-lived. They say
prices could fall as early as next year under pressure from an increase in
milk on the European market resulting from the Gatt world trade deal, which
will limit dairy exports and increase imports into the EU.
New dairy body chief, Page 11
</TEXT>
