<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Negative equity may not be as severe as recent estimates
suggest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The problem of negative equity in the housing market - when the outstanding
mortgage on a home is larger than the value of the property  - may not be as
severe as recent estimates of its total value suggest, according to the Bank
of England's report yesterday, Motoko Rich writes.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank said the total estimated value
of negative equity - Pounds 5.6bn - obscured the fact that a high proportion
of affected households had very small gaps between mortgage and property
values.
The Bank said that of an estimated 1.1m households with negative equity,
more than one-third had shortfalls of less than Pounds 2,000, while more
than half had gaps of less than Pounds 5,000. Only 3 per cent had shortfalls
exceeding Pounds 15,000.
A 5 per cent increase in UK average house prices across all regions would
cut the total value of negative equity by about two-fifths, while a 10 per
cent increase in house prices would reduce it by more than two-thirds, the
Bank said. The south-east, Greater London, the south-west and East Anglia
accounted for 95 per cent of the total value.
</TEXT>
