<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Shift on taxation of life insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Changes in the taxation of life insurance, to enable UK life insurers to
compete more effectively in the rest of Europe, are to be introduced by the
government in the next finance bill.
The most important shift will affect taxation of 'services business' where
the insurer does not have to have an office in the country in which the
policyholder lives.
This has been allowed only since the changes in European law on life
insurance which took effect at the beginning of July.
The UK taxes income to policyholders as it builds up in the funds. Most
other European countries tax income when it is withdrawn from the fund and
reaches the individual.
Sir George Young, Treasury financial secretary, said the British tax system
already took account of this difference between tax regimes in the way it
treated business carried out through overseas branches of UK life insurers.
The changes represent an extension of that arrangement.
The new system will apply from the next new accounting period. For most life
insurers this will mean it will affect business written in 1995.
Another likely change, but one which has not been announced, is the closing
of a loophole in the existing system to make sure that the investment
element of offshore reinsurance does not slip through the tax net.
While these alterations will be welcomed by life insurers, they have not
resolved the wider debate within the UK life insurance industry on whether
there should be more widespread changes to harmonise UK and European tax
regimes.
The Association of British Insurers is expected to start discussions soon
with the Inland Revenue about the implication of any further fundamental
shift in the tax arrangements towards the European model.
</TEXT>
