<HEADLINE>
FT  02 NOV 94 / Benn publishes details of MPs' cash probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The House of Commons investigation into the so-called 'cash-for-questions'
affair broke up in disarray last night after the veteran Labour MP Mr Tony
Benn defied parliamentary rules and published details of the inquiry's
private deliberations.
The clash on the powerful privileges committee came as Mr Peter Preston,
editor of The Guardian, faced an investigation by MPs into his newspaper's
use of a doctored Commons letterhead during its inquiries into the payment
of a Cabinet minister's hotel bill.
Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker, yesterday cleared the way for an
emergency Commons debate today, which is expected to lead to a decision that
the newspaper should be the subject of a privileges committee probe.
Her decision followed a direct attack on the Guardian editor by Mr John
Major, the prime minister. He told the Commons: 'If it is commonly accepted
in journalism that the end justifies any means, then I believe journalism
will regret stooping to that particular standard.'
Mr Preston, already facing a barrage of criticism from Tory MPs, last night
announced he had resigned from the Press Complaints Commission, the
self-regulatory organisation which adjudicates on complaints against
newspapers.
Mr Preston said he had decided 'the cleanest thing' he could do was to 'make
the break' with the commission. He stressed in his letter to Lord McGregor,
the commission's chairman, that his resignation was not an admission that
his conduct deliberately flouted the code of practice. 'I do not believe it
did and did not believe it last November when the events so copiously
described took place,' he said.
Hopes of a cross-party agreement at Westminster on the way in which the
Commons should investigate charges against individual MPs suffered a severe
setback when Mr Benn stuck to his insistence that the proceedings should be
published.
A statement released after the two-hour meeting of the privileges committee,
which was due to investigate charges against two Tory MPs alleged to have
accepted payment for tabling questions, said it could not interview
witnesses without giving them 'the opportunity to consider . . . the
position created by Mr Benn's statement'.
Mr Benn, a former cabinet minister, published the committee's private
deliberations last night as 'my own reports of its proceedings'.
His six-page account of the meeting shows that the Conservative members
argued strongly against interviewing the two MPs facing investigation - Mr
Graham Riddick and Mr David Tredinnick - as long as he insisted on
publication.
Mr Benn now faces the threat of a Commons motion to order his expulsion from
the privileges committee, a move unprecedented in recent times. The
committee itself is not expected to meet again until after the opening of
the new session of parliament on November 16.
The meeting was attended by the committee's seven Labour members, who have
been boycotting its deliberations over the government's insistence that
hearings be held in private.
Meanwhile Sir Paul Beresford, the housing minister who is the latest target
of press allegations, denied any wrongdoing over combining government duties
with part-time work as a dentist.
Solicitors acting for Mr Mohamed Fayed, owner of Harrods, yesterday wrote to
Mrs Barbara Mills, the director of public prosecutions, to call for an
urgent decision on whether he would face criminal charges for his alleged
attempts to 'blackmail' the government.
Today's debate is expected to be on a motion calling for The Guardian to be
investigated by the privileges committee.
Announcing the debate to MPs yesterday, Miss Boothroyd said the 'essential'
issue was: 'The alleged action of The Guardian newspaper in representing
that a letter sent by it to the Ritz hotel in Paris was sent in the name of
a member of this house.'
</TEXT>
