<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / (CORRECTED) Lautro raps life company's pension deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 3rd November 1994) appended to this article.
Small employers who bought off-the-peg occupation pension schemes from Crown
Life sales agents following poor investment advice may be eligible for
compensation, says Lautro, the self-regulating body for the insurance
industry.
According to the Occupational Pensions Advisory Service more than 4,700 of
about 5,500 group occupational schemes sold by Crown Life have been wound
up.
The advisory service said that in many cases independent trustees to the
schemes are finding it impossible to reconcile pension assets with scheme
members because record-keeping was so poor.
Lautro, whose work is being taken over by the Personal Investment Authority,
said yesterday that in inspection visits to Century Life, which acquired the
pensions business from Crown Life in January last year, it found
'significant breaches of Lautro rules covering compliance procedures and the
quality of investment advice'.
Mr Don Hall, chief executive of the advisory service, said Crown Life sales
agents sold group 'defined benefit' schemes to small employers for whom they
were probably inappropriate. Complaints from members of Crown Life schemes
accounted for a disproportionate number of the complaints received about
schemes administered by insurance companies.
Lautro said its monitoring committee outlined the requirement for a
comprehensive review of the business and 'appropriate corrective measures in
relation to management of the sales operation and the compensation of
investors where appropriate'.
It had decided that a full hearing before its disciplinary committee was
unwarranted because Century had taken steps to place the business of Crown
on a proper regulatory basis.
Lautro said Century 'had good reason to believe that an acceptable state of
compliance existed' in Crown's business.
CORRECTION
The criticisms by Lautro reported in Tuesday's Financial Times under the
heading 'Lautro raps life company's pension deals' related to CCL Assurance,
not to Crown Life as inaccurately stated in the report. Century Life has
acquired the pensions business both of CCL Assurance and of Crown Life and
there has been no criticism by Lautro of Crown Life.
</TEXT>
