<DATE>941101
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / World Trade News: Japan and US miss glass pact deadline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan and the US have failed to finalise an accord to give US manufacturers
better access to the Japanese market for flat glass.
Negotiators from the two sides met into the early hours of this morning but
could not agree on details of an accord that was agreed in principle a month
ago. They had set yesterday as the deadline for wrapping up the agreement.
'We made real progress, but there are still technical and practical problems
to resolve,' said an official of the Japanese Ministry of International
Trade and Industry. He indicated negotiations would be re-sumed though no
date had yet been set for another round of talks.
Lack of agreement by the deadline could prompt the US into taking unilateral
trade action, possibly sanctions, against Japan's flat glass market.
Negotiations had been going on since last Wednesday. Mr Hideaki Kumano,
vice-minister for international trade and industry, voiced the hope
yesterday that the two sides might still settle the glass talks by the
deadline.
The talks are a remnant of the bilateral framework negotiations in which
Japan and the US reached a partial agreement a month ago.
At that time, the issue of flat glass, as well as Japan's market for
vehicles and vehicle parts, was postponed when Japan and the US announced
they had reached agreement in four of the five sectors targeted in the
negotiations. An accord on the glass market had been reached 'in principle,'
the Japanese government said at the time, leaving only the details to be
worked out within 30 days.
Mr Steve Farrar, director of international business for Guardian Industries,
a US glass maker, said yesterday most differences had been resolved. As with
other US-Japan disputes, stalemate has emerged over US efforts to pin down
specific criteria to measure progress.
'We want to avoid having a situation where importers could buy token amounts
and never become serious customers,' he said. 'We want to be sure that what
is being measured is substantial business relationships.'
The US claims that Japan's flat glass market, which is the second largest in
the world at Dollars 4.5bn a year, is closed to foreign suppliers.
This is because of the dominance of three large domestic producers which
have very tightly controlled distribution arrangements with the industry's
wholesalers.
US makers have only a 1 per cent share of the Japanese market, compared with
more than 25 per cent in Europe and Latin America, the US says. Under these
circumstances, the US would like to see more procurement of US-made glass
for facilities owned by the government in addition to greater market access
in the private sector.
The Japanese side has claimed that its market, with imports amounting to 12
per cent, compares favourably to that in the US, where imports are a meagre
5 per cent and in Europe, where foreign-made flat glass accounts for 17 per
cent of the market.
The Japanese government has been reluctant to interfere in what it considers
a matter for the private sector. The basic stance of the government is that
if US companies want a larger share of the Japanese market they should raise
their competitiveness.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
    P3211 Flat Glass.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
