<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Military aids push on Rio crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK MCCURRY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Brazilian federal government and the state government of Rio de Janeiro
agreed yesterday on a military-led crackdown on drug gangs, arms
trafficking, police corruption and crime in the city. President Itamar
Franco and Rio governor Nilo Batista agreed on creation of a unified
crime-fighting organ with the military directing united operations of the
state-controlled military and civil police, justice secretariat and civil
defence secretariat. The army will supply the police with the same heavy
weapons used by drug gangs. The federal government has been under media
pressure to intervene in the city's shanty towns, many controlled by
heavily-armed drug dealers, after violence including the deaths of at least
13 people by stray bullets in October.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BRZ  Brazil, South America.
</CN>
