<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Change promised in Macedonia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SKOPJE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Macedonia's President Kiro Gligorov promised yesterday to press for reforms
and better relations with his country's neighbours after his party won a
two-thirds majority in elections boycotted by the opposition. His Alliance
for Macedonia party said at a news conference it had won 88 of parliament's
120 seats. State television earlier put the figure at 83. 'We shall have to
tackle the reforms we have already started in our political sphere, our
judiciary and the economy, including privatisation of state enterprises,'
said Mr Gligorov. Commenting on relations with Greece, which has blockaded
his landlocked country, he said he wanted an agreement as soon as possible,
and expressed hope for a compromise on the issues of Macedonia's name, flag
and constitution, as demanded by Athens.
</TEXT>
