<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / International Company News: Interpublic to acquire media
buyer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Interpublic, the US advertising group, said it would acquire Western
International Media, the country's largest independent media-buying company,
in a deal which appeared to signal a consolidation of the US media-buying
industry.
The deal could also indicate a push by the US group into the media-buying
business in Europe, which is currently dominated by locally-based groups. Mr
Dennis Holt, Western's president, said the link with Interpublic would give
his customers access to European markets through the adver-tising group's
offices there.
Media buyers purchase advertising space in bulk and sell it on to
advertisers, either directly or through other agencies. The greater
bargaining power available to big buyers has prompted a consolidation in the
European industry.
The acquisition of Western, which claims to buy Dollars 1.6bn of air time
and other advertising space a year, could indicate an acceleration of the
same trend in the US. It represents the first big acquisition by
Interpublic, which has annual billings of Dollars 15bn and whose agencies
include McCann-Erickson, Lintas and the Lowe group. These agencies each
currently buy their own media space.
The planned deal prompted other advertising industry executives to suggest
that Interpublic was preparing to merge all its activities in this area into
one company, creating a giant in the US media-buying industry.
However, a spokesman for Interpublic denied that the Western acquisition
would lead to a merging of the media-buying operations: 'We have no
intention of combining them. It's a free-standing acquisition.'
This was seen in part as an attempt to ease concerns among the many smaller
US advertising agencies which currently use Western to buy their media
space.
European-based advertisers have also been exploring ways to expand their US
media-buying muscle. Saatchi &amp; Saatchi, which in 1989 combined its European
media buying activities in a single company, Zenith, is currently studying
whether to adopt the same course in the US.
Together with the acquisition of an independent media-buyer, Saatchi
estimates the consolidation of its activities in Zenith has given it about a
sixth of the total European market.
The terms of yesterday's deal were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
