<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / MPs call for stronger controls on out-of-town superstores
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further construction of out-of-town shopping centres and superstores should
be restricted to protect the environment, a report by an all-party Commons
select committee is expected to recommend today.
The findings by the House of Commons Environment Committee will mark another
attack on large developments in the countryside, which encourage greater use
of cars by locating shops far away from residential areas.
Last week the Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution proposed doubling
petrol tax and halving spending on new roads in an effort to avoid
unacceptable environmental damage in the early decades of the next century.
The environment select committee's inquiry, Shopping Centres and their
Future, began in the spring and will call for stronger curbs against
out-of-town developments which take trade away from existing town centres.
It recommends that planning guidance issued by the government be amended 'to
include a presumption that superstores are best located in or on the edge of
town centres unless there are very strong indications to the contrary'.
This proposal would go further than a guidance note issued to local planning
authorities last July by the Environment Department, stressing the
importance of stemming the decline of town centres by encouraging high
street development. This said that out-of-town developments should not be
refused, 'unless there is clear evidence to suggest that the result would be
to undermine the vitality and viability of that (town) centre'.
If adopted, the select committee's proposals would add to the pressure on
large retailers, which have been finding it increasingly difficult to
receive planning permission for out-of-town sites since the guidance note
was issued.
Tesco, the UK's second-largest supermarket group, says that while it used to
win about 60 per cent of planning cases that went to appeal, the percentage
has dropped to 10 or 15 since last year's guidance note.
The UK's three largest food retailers, J. Sainsbury, Tesco and Argyll, owner
of Safeway, have recently cut back out-of-town expansion in favour of town
centre developments.
Mr David Sainsbury, chairman of the grocery chain, said recently: 'We are
now taking a different view about the closure of town centre stores,
believing that by remodelling and refurbishing these stores, we can give
them a new lease of life. We also believe that as an industry we should seek
to locate more of our stores near high streets while making certain that
they have good car parking.'
The select committee's recommendations are likely to be welcomed by
environmental groups such as the Council for the Protection of Rural
England, which has lobbied for stricter controls on out-of-town development.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
