<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Observer: Railroaded
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Running a company during a heated takeover battle sure is stressful. It
seems to have taken a particularly tough toll on Drew Lewis, chairman of
Union Pacific, battling to win control of rival US railroad operator Santa
Fe Pacific.
On Sunday, after raising its bid for Santa Fe to Dollars 3.8bn to top
Burlington Northern's rival offer of Dollars 3.2bn, Union Pacific announced
that Lewis, a former transportation secretary in the Reagan administration,
is taking a leave of four to six weeks to enter an alcohol-treatment
programme.
Will this affect the outcome of the bid struggle? Union Pacific will clearly
miss him; no fewer than three senior executives are taking on Lewis's duties
in his absence.
</TEXT>
